  <h2>I Buy Houses All Over Wichita</h2>
  <p>Wichita's big. About 400,000 people spread across a huge footprint, and the housing market varies wildly depending on where you are. A home in College Hill with original hardwoods and a 1930s foundation sits next to a ranch on the east side built in 1962. A renovated Victorian in Riverside is a world away from the newer stuff pushing out toward Maize and Goddard. I understand these neighborhoods because I work in them constantly, and I buy in all of them.</p>
  <p>If you're sitting on a house you need to sell — whether it's tied up in an estate, damaged from a fire, falling apart from deferred maintenance, or you just want cash and speed — I'm here to buy it. No games, no timeline pressure, fair money.</p>

  <h2>Wichita's Housing Market Right Now</h2>
  <p>Wichita's market is wide open because Wichita itself is wide. You've got everything from distressed east-side properties in the $80k range where landlords have abandoned tenants, all the way up to $400k+ homes in College Hill, Crown Heights, and west Wichita where old money and estate-home buyers operate. The sweet spot for most sales I make is between $120k and $250k — older established neighborhoods with real bones and real problems.</p>
  <p>The city's also split by major employer geography. Boeing and Spirit AeroSystems workers live everywhere, but there are clusters near south Wichita and east Wichita. A lot of Wichita homes need foundation work because the clay soil movement is real, especially in homes built pre-1980. That's baked into how I price. I also see roofing, HVAC, and electrical issues crop up constantly in the 1950s-1970s stock that makes up huge chunks of the city.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Wichita</h2>
  <p>Wichita sellers are diverse because Wichita is diverse. I buy from people who inherited a house from a parent who owned it for 40 years and now the estate needs to settle. I buy from landlords absolutely done with tenants and maintenance costs. I buy from people going through divorce where the house is a liability, not an asset. I see people facing foreclosure, liens, property tax problems. I buy fire-damaged homes, homes with mold, homes where major systems have failed.</p>
  <p>I also buy from people who just want simple — they need to relocate for work at Boeing or Koch Industries, or they bought wrong and need out. Estate sales are constant in neighborhoods like College Hill and Riverside where families bought in the 1970s and the original owners are aging out. That's real money on the table, but it takes time to liquidate through traditional means.</p>

