  <h2>Wichita-Specific Questions I Get Asked</h2>
  <div class="faq-section">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Do you buy in East Wichita? I've heard it's harder to sell there.</h3>
      <p>Yes, absolutely. East Wichita is where I buy the most volume. Yes, values are lower, but that's already factored into my offer. A house that would list for $110k and sit 90 days on the MLS with needed updates gets a fair cash offer from me in 24 hours. That's the whole point.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>What about homes near Boeing or Spirit facilities? Do those sell differently?</h3>
      <p>They do get affected by layoffs and relocations, which is actually good for me because relocating Boeing or Spirit employees need to sell fast. The neighborhoods aren't as affected by soil conditions or age as other parts of Wichita, so I can price more aggressively. Not a problem at all.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>I have a 1940s home in College Hill with foundation problems. Will you actually make an offer?</h3>
      <p>Yes. I specifically buy homes like that. Foundation work on old Wichita clay soil homes is expensive — $15k-$40k often. I factor that in and make a real offer. You get paid fairly and we handle the repair.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h3>Do I have to be inside Wichita city limits, or do you buy in Sedgwick County too?</h3>
      <p>I buy all over Sedgwick County. Wichita proper, suburbs, unincorporated areas. Doesn't matter to me. If the property is in Sedgwick County or the surrounding areas I service, I'll evaluate it.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

